Linear Regression Assumptions¶

Linear Regression Assumptions The multiple linear regression model uses all of the assumptions of the classical simple (a.k.a. two-variable) linear regression model, but also assumes that the independent variables are not collinear. Assumption of a multiple linear regression model are as follows:

  • A linear relationship exists between the dependent and independent variables.
  • The independent variables are not correlated with the error (disturbance) term: corr(X1i, εi) = corr(X1i, εi) = 0. If X1i and X2i are nonstochastic (i.e., X1i and X2i are fixed numbers) then the condition is satisfied.
  • The conditional expectation of the error given Xi is zero: E(εi|X1i) = E(εi|X2i) = 0.
  • The variance of the error terms is constant for all observations (homoskedasticity).
  • The error term of one observation is not correlated with that of another observation.
  • The model is correctly specified in that it includes only the appropriate independent variables and does not omit variables.
  • The independent variables are not collinear (i.e., the independent variables are not random, and there is no exact linear relation between any two or more independent variables). In the simple regression case, this means there is no expression of one independent variable in terms of another: X2i = A0 + A1 × X1i. This expression does not have an error or residual term, which means that it represents a perfectly collinear relationship.
  • Only the meaningful variables should be included.
  • The independent variables should be independent of each other. That is, the model should have little or no multicollinearity.
  • The independent variables are linearly related to the dependent variable.
  • Linear regression requires quite large sample sizes.

Keeping the above assumptions in mind, let’s look at our dataset.

The dataset comes from Intrinsic Value, and it is related to valuation engagements of Israeli privately-held companies. The regression goal is to predict the enterprise value of a privately-held company (variable y). The dataset can be downloaded from here.

Input variables¶

  • valuationdate: the specific point in time as of which the valuator’s opinion of value applies (categorical).
  • revenues: the LTM (last twelve months) revenues of the company, as reported in the company’s statement of income, as of the valuation date (numeric).
  • ebit : the LTM (last twelve months) operating income (revenues minus (cost of goods sold minus selling, general & administrative expenses minus research and development expenses) of the company, as reported in the company’s statement of income, as of the valuation date (numeric).
  • depreciation: the LTM (last twelve months) depreciation and amortization of the company, as reported in the company’s statement of cash flow, as of the valuation date (numeric).
  • capex: the LTM (last twelve months) capital expenditures of the company, as reported in the company’s statement of cash flow, as of the valuation date (numeric).
  • ncwc: the non-cash working capital (current assets excluding cash and marketable securities minus current liabilities excluding interest bearing debt) of the company, as reported on the company’s balance sheet, as of the valuation date (numeric).
  • bv: the book value of common equity of the company, as reported on the company’s balance sheet, as of the valuation date (numeric).

Predict variable (desired target):¶

  • y — the enterprise value of a privately-held, based on a DCF valuation performed by intrinsic value, as of the valuation date (numeric).

Splitting the Dataset into Train and Test Sets¶

Learning the parameters of a prediction function and testing it on the same data is a methodological mistake: a model that would just repeat the labels of the samples that it has just seen would have a perfect score but would fail to predict anything useful on yet-unseen data.

his situation is called overfitting. To avoid it, it is common practice when performing a (supervised) machine learning experiment to hold out part of the available data as a test set X_test, y_test.

Note that the word “experiment” is not intended to denote academic use only, because even in commercial settings machine learning usually starts out experimentally.

In [71]:
X = data_final.loc[:, data_final.columns != 'y']
y = data_final.loc[:, data_final.columns == 'y']

Recursive Feature Elimination¶

Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) is based on the idea to repeatedly construct a model and choose either the best or worst performing feature, setting the feature aside and then repeating the process with the rest of the features. This process is applied until all features in the dataset are exhausted. The goal of RFE is to select features by recursively considering smaller and smaller sets of features.

In [72]:
data_final_vars=data_final.columns.values.tolist()
y1=["y"]
X1=[i for i in data_final_vars if i not in y1]

from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

lin = LinearRegression()
rfe = RFE(lin, 6)
rfe = rfe.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())
print(rfe.support_)
print(rfe.ranking_)

The R2 (a.k.a. R squared or coefficient of determination) is a measure of a regression algorithm’s precision. Best possible score for R2 is 1.0 and it can be negative (because the model can be arbitrarily worse). A constant model that always predicts the expected value of y, disregarding the input features, would get a R2 score of 0.0.

Predicting the test set results and calculating the precision¶

In [79]:
y_pred = lin.predict(X_test)
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
print("Linear Regression R squared of the test set is: {:.2f}".format(r2_score(y_test, y_pred)))

Linear Regression R squared of the test set is: 0.61

So, in our model, 60.75% of the variability in Y can be explained using X. This is not that exciting.

Compute MSE, RMSE and MAE¶

The MSE is the mean squared error regression loss. MSE is a measure of a regression algorithm's accuracy. As it is derived from the square of Euclidean distance, it is always a positive value with the error decreasing as the error approaches zero.

In [80]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
print("Linear Regression MSE of the test set is: {:.2f}".format(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))

Linear Regression MSE of the test set is: 54901555988.12

The RMSE is the root mean squared error regression loss. RMSE is a measure of a regression algorithm's accuracy. As it is derived from the square root of the square of Euclidean distance, it is always a positive value with the error decreasing as the error approaches zero.

In [81]:
lin_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_pred, y_test))
print("Linear Regression RMSE of the test set is: {:.2f}".format(lin_rmse))

Linear Regression RMSE of the test set is: 234310.81

Our model was able to predict the enterprise value of every privately-held company in the test set within $234,310.81 thousands of dollars of the real value.

The MAE is the mean absolute error regression loss. The MAE is a measure of a regression algorithm's accuracy. As it is derived from the Manhattan distance (i.e., the absolute value of Euclidean distance), it is always a positive value with the error decreasing as the error approaches zero.

In [82]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error
print("Linear Regression MAE of the test set is: {:.2f}".format(mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)))

Linear Regression MAE of the test set is: 130757.81
